# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: askam-trucks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:askam-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The brand's name was derived from the Turkish name of Anatolia (*Anadolu*) and its logo was the Hittite stag.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Production of the Anadol passenger cars was discontinued in 1986, while the production of the Otosan 500 Pick-Up continued until 1991.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] At present, Otosan builds Ford Motor Company's passenger cars and commercial vehicles, which are exported to numerous countries in the world, particularly to the European Union member states.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The Anadol A1, code named FW5 by Reliant which developed the prototype upon Anadol's request, went into production on 19 December 1966.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The styling of the A1 was by Tom Karen of Ogle Design.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1967, a New Zealand entrepreneur, Alan Gibbs, announced that he intended to also produce the car in his country as the Anziel Nova.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] This project never proceeded beyond the initial announcement and prototype.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Production of the A1 started at Otosan's new eastside Istanbul plant on 16 December 1966 with the 1200 cc Cortina engine, but in October 1968, it was replaced with the stronger 1300 cc Kent engine.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1969, the dashboard gauges were updated with a new design and their positions were changed, while the ergonomic design of the steering wheel was improved.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1970, the two round headlamps at the front were replaced with oval headlamps, a new transmission system was introduced, and the bumpers were changed.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1971, the interior of the roof was covered with vinyl, in accordance with the fashion of that period.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The design essentially remained this way until April 1972.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1971, a special model of the A1 was developed in dedication to the Mediterranean Games in İzmir, called the *Akdeniz* (Mediterranean).
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Anadol Akdeniz was like a prelude of the new model which arrived in 1972, and had bumpers which were integrated into the shape of the bodywork, a different front grille, rectangular headlamps with white signal lamps, and different rear lights.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The interior of the car was also completely changed, with a new dashboard, new seats and new finishing materials.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Starting from 1972, this model became the standard coupé of Anadol until its production was stopped in 1975.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The five-seat body was built from fibre glass and affixed to a h-frame chassis.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The Anadol was originally only available as a coupé, but in late 1973 was joined by a saloon (sedan) and an estate version.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The chassis had independent front suspension utilising coil springs and leaf springs on a live axle for the rear.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Brakes were disc in the front and drum in the rear.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The steering system used a recirculating ball mechanism.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Anadol A1 was also the first Turkish rally car, and *Anadol Ralli Takımı (ART)* became the first Turkish rally team.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The first official rally in Turkey, the 1968 Trakya (Thrace) Rally, was won by the famous duo of Anadol A1 pilots, Renç Koçibey and Demir Bükey.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Other famous Anadol A1 rally pilots included Romolo Marcopoli, İskender Atakan, Claude (Klod) Nahum, Mete Oktar, Şükrü Okçu and Serdar Bostancı.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Still in 1968, another Turkish driver, İskender Aruoba, participated in the 30,000 km Africa-Asia-Europe Tour, which lasted 8 months, with his Anadol A1.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Anadol A2 was both Anadol's first four-door model, and the first fiberglass bodied four-door sedan in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Its prototype was prepared in 1969 and the car was introduced to the market in 1970.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Apart from having four doors and a single wide front bench seat for both the driver and the passenger, the first versions of the A2 shared the same technical specifications with the A1.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Starting from April 1972, the front part of the A2 received the same changes that the A1 received that year (including the new nose, front grille and headlamps) and this design went on until the end of 1975.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1976, a new version of the A2, the SL, was introduced.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The biggest changes in the exterior appearance of the car were made in the front and the back, with new lamps.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Particularly, the rear lamps had a completely new appearance.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The interior was also completely changed, with a new steering wheel, new dashboard and new finishing materials.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The A2 was also the first Anadol model which received extensive crash tests in order to improve the safety of the car.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Since the A2 was primarily designed as a family sedan, and was also suitable for commercial uses (usually as a taxi), it became the best-selling Anadol passenger car, with a total of 35,668 units sold.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The A2 was replaced by the A8-16 in 1981.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In trying to fill a need for light transport, the first prototype pickup truck (on A1 basis) was developed by Bernar Nahum in 1970.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Serial production began the following year, equipped with the 1.3-liter Ford Crossflow engine also used in saloons.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The P2 also received the new nose of the facelifted A1.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In the 1980s, this was upgraded to the 1.6-liter Ford Pinto, as seen in other Anadols as well.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] After 1983, the 600D version was released, with a 1.9-liter diesel engine, which necessitated a slight bulge in the hood.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Always high in demand, and used extensively by the Turkish Post (PTT), the pickup continued to be in production until 1991, when 36,892 had been built.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Many saloons have also been converted to pickup trucks.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] A sports model, the STC-16, was produced between 1973 and 1975.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The first prototype was introduced in 1972.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Designed by Eralp Noyan, the STC-16 was the first Turkish sports car.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] It was also the second Turkish-designed car after Devrim, which was produced in 1961 as the first Turkish designed and built automobile.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The engine of Ford Escort and some of the components of Ford Capri produced by Ford of Europe were also used in the Anadol STC-16.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The 1598 cc crossflow engine used in the Anadol STC-16 was originally developed for the 1970 Ford Escort Mexico, the special-edition road version of the Ford Escort rally car which won the 1970 London to Mexico World Cup Rally.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1971, Erdoğan Gönül, the General Manager of Otosan and the son-in-law of Vehbi Koç, convinced the latter on the production of a sports car.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The car was aimed at the upper segment of the Turkish market and would participate in international rallies, thus bringing prestige to the Anadol brand.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The creation works of the STC-16 were assigned to Turkish designer Eralp Noyan, who had graduated from the Royal Fine Arts Academy in Belgium.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The STC-16 was a completely new Anadol and looked nothing like the previous models of the brand, although it had similarities with other sports car models of that period, such as the Datsun 240Z and Ginetta G21.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The car's name, "STC-16", was originally an acronym for "Sports Turkish Car 1600", but as it was also intended for international markets, STC was alternatively named as the "Sports Touring Coupé".
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Among the Turkish youth, however, STC was popularly interpreted as "Süper Türk Canavarı" (Super Turkish Monster).
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The STC-16 used a shortened and modified Anadol chassis and suspension system, while using a 1600 cc Ford Mexico engine.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The transmission system, on the other hand, was the one that was used by some high performance Cortina and Capri models in the United Kingdom.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The STC-16 had all the typical dashboard gauges and indicators which the British and Italian sports cars of that period had.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Apart from the speed and rpm indicators, a resettable cruise distance indicator (something new for that period) as well as a Lucas ampermeter and Smiths oil, fuel and engine temperature indicators were installed on the dashboard.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Following an initial development period of 11 months, the first three prototypes of the STC-16 became ready for road tests, which took place at the Cengiz Topel Naval Air Station along the D.100 highway (back then known as the E-5 highway), in the town of Köseköy within Kocaeli Province.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The first crash tests of the STC-16 were also performed in this period.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Afterwards, the STC-16 was taken to England by Nihat Atasagun, Otosan's Production Manager, who tested the car at the MIRA circuit.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The car received great attention at the streets and highways of England, where most people thought it was the prototype of a new British sports car.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Several traffic police officers stopped the car in England, which had a special testing licence plate, "320-E", interested in finding out more information about the new model.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The STC-16 was tested by British drivers at the circuit, and modifications were made according to their suggestions, following which the car's performance and safety characteristics were improved.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Finally, at the beginning of April 1973, the first STC-16 rolled out of the Otosan factory in Istanbul and went into the showroom.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The global oil crisis of 1973 meant bad news for the STC-16.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Not only car fuel became more expensive, but the cost of building fiberglass (which is a petrochemical product) car bodies such as that of the STC-16 also skyrocketed.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The rear-wheel drive STC-16 had a relatively high fuel consumption, and the sports coupé market in Turkey appealed to a very small segment, particularly to the young members of high-income families.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Unlike other Anadol models of that period which were sold for 50,000 to 55,000 Turkish Liras, the STC-16 had a price tag of more than 70,000 Turkish Liras.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] When all these factors came together, the primary customers of the STC-16 remained the rally drivers, sports car enthusiasts and young celebrities.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] A total of 176 Anadol STC-16s have been produced between 1973 and 1975, the majority of them in 1973, until the global oil crisis in that year reduced demand and slowed down production.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Most of the STC-16s were painted in "Alanya Yellow", which became synonymous with the car.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Some of them were red with white racing stripes, and some white with blue racing stripes, as it was fashionable with the sports cars of that period.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Instead of the heavy steel chassis of the road version STC-16, the rally version had a lightweight FRP chassis, combined with a modified 140 bhp (104 kW; 142 PS) engine.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The STC-16 became synonymous with its era in the memory of that period's Turkish youth, and the upgraded motorsports version of the car won numerous victories in rally competitions in Turkey and Europe.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Famous Anadol rally drivers in the 1970s included Renç Koçibey, Demir Bükey, Romolo Marcopoli, İskender Aruoba, Cihat Gürkan, Ali Furgaç, Şevki Gökerman and Serdar Bostancı.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The SV–1600, which headed to the showrooms at the end of 1973, was the world's first fiberglass-bodied 5-door station wagon (estate) car.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] It had a completely different design and appearance than the 4-door Anadol models, and was inspired by Reliant's Scimitar sports-station coupé.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Several details of the car bore similarities with the station wagon designs of Bertone and Pininfarina in that period.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The first examples of the SV–1600 had single-colour paint, while the front hood had a spoiler, which was something new for station cars.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] After some time, a more luxurious version was produced, and bi-colour paint was applied, while new interiors were introduced.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Starting from 1976, the SV-1600 received aluminium wheels, a new steering wheel, new side mirrors, and a single-colour paint with a black-and-white stripe on the sides.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The car also had retractable seats for further enlarging the trunk space.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Production of the SV–1600 continued until 1982.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The *Böcek* (Bug) was designed by Jan Nahum, who worked at Otosan's Design and Development Department in this period.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Later in his career, Nahum became the General Manager of major companies like Otokar and Tofaş, the Head of International Business Development at FIAT, and later yet the CEO of Petrol Ofisi.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Jan Nahum's father, Bernar Nahum, played an important role in the establishment of the Anadol factory and the development of the Anadol A1.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Another close family relative, Claude (Klod) Nahum, was an Anadol A1 rally racer, as well as the developer of the Otosan Anadol Wankel engine.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] He is currently a founding partner of the KIRAÇA Group of Companies, which also includes KARSAN Automotive Industries.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The vehicle, similar in appearance to a fiberglass dune buggy but different in design concept and characteristics, was developed upon request for a similar vehicle by the Turkish Armed Forces.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Otosan also predicted that the rising popularity of Turkey's tourism and beach resorts would guarantee a certain level of demand for a civilian-use version of such a vehicle.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The Böcek's roof could be opened, it didn't have any doors, and its windshield had the same inclination as the hood.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The futuristic front panel and gauges of the Böcek were ahead of their time, and were used many years later by future passenger vehicles in Europe.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The Böcek had a 1298 cc 63 bhp (47 kW; 64 PS) Ford engine, which provided very good performance given the vehicle's small dimensions.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In line with the pop-art designs of that period, the Böcek had asymmetrical front and rear ends.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The front grille was asymmetrical, while in the rear, there were 3 lights at the left and 2 at the right.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The rearview mirror, which was formed of five differently angled mirrors which provided a telescopic view, was mounted on top of the windshield.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The front tyres were 225*55*13 in dimension, while the seats were fiberglass covered with vinyl.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Several different versions of the Böcek (Bug) were designed for institutional and civilian use.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] There was a version with gull-wing doors, a version for the Turkish Radio and Television Corporation (TRT) which was optimized for using film and video cameras, an off road version, a tractor/trailer version, and a military version.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The Böcek was a design concept that was ahead of its time, but just like the STC-16, it was not a great seller due to the economic situation in Turkey and the rest of the world in that period, caused mostly by the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Only 203 examples of the Böcek were produced between 1975 and 1977.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Production of the 4-door, 5-seat A8-16 series began in 1981.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] However, it also had details that appeared obsolete in 1981, such as the rear lights which were originally used in the Anadol Böcek, but didn't look good on the A8-16.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The interior design and the materials used also did not please the traditional Anadol customers.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Many of the design characteristics, especially the door windows and frames, were borrowed from older Anadol models such as the SV-1600 which was designed in 1973, and most potential customers saw this car as a hotchpotch of old Anadol spare parts, mixed with some new ideas.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The new body still sat on a box-type perimeter frame with crossmembers, an independent coil spring front suspension and a live, leaf spring rear axle.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Steering is rack and pinion, transmission by the way of a four-speed manual.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Even the higher performance 1.6 Pinto E-Max engine, which was used in the first A8-16s that were produced between 1981 and 1982, could not improve the popularity of these cars.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] As a result, in order to reduce production costs, this engine was no longer used in the A8-16 SL models of 1983–1984 which reverted to the older 1.6 engine.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Only 1,013 examples of the A8-16 were produced between 1981 and 1984.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Otosan Design and Development Department employed many talented engineers, such as Claude (Klod) Nahum, who led the group which developed a Wankel engine that could produce more than 100 PS (74 kW) despite its small size.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] But due to its high development costs and the well-known problematic character of Wankel engines, this engine was not used in Anadol's models.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Today, one of these Wankel engines is displayed at the Rahmi M.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] In 1977 Marcello Gandini designed the *FW 11* for Anadol and Reliant, the latter naming it as the *Scimitar SE 7*.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Four prototypes of this car were produced, two of which remained in England with Reliant badging, and two other examples, one of them white and the other one blue, were sent to Turkey with the Anadol badge.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The car, which had a modern design and "luxuries" for that period's European cars such as electric windows, was deemed too expensive to produce profitably by Anadol and the project was shelved.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The two Anadol prototypes were held in Koç Holding's (which owns Otosan) depot in Istanbul's Acıbadem district for nearly 25 years.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Since 2004 one of them is occasionally displayed at the Rahmi M.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] One of the other prototypes, the *Reliant Scimitar SE 7*, is currently displayed in England.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Following Anadol's decision not to build the FW 11, Reliant exhibited the Scimitar SE 7 at its stand as a prototype during the Birmingham Motor Show.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The FW 11's overall design themes were recycled by Gandini for the Citroën BX, premiered in 1982.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] During the late 1970s, Jan Nahum developed several prototypes and worked on new Anadol designs.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Many of these new prototypes, which even included full-scale models, however, could not be mass-produced.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Otosan, in that period, aimed at creating modern cars, in line with the developments of the automotive industry worldwide, while reducing the amount of fiberglass which it used for building the body parts of its vehicles.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] To meet this demand, Jan Nahum designed and built two different prototypes of the Anadol *Çağdaş* (meaning *Contemporary*).
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The bodywork of Çağdaş was made of fiberglass parts fitted on a steel skeleton.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The Wankel engine developed by Claude (Klod) Nahum was installed on it.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Turkish newspapers made detailed coverage of the car, stating that production would begin either in 1980 or 1981.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] However, due to the political, social and economic instability in the country, the project could never be realized.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] A single prototype of Çağdaş is today displayed at the Rahmi M.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The A9, designed by Bertone in 1982, was the last prototype of Anadol.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] It was a 4-door sedan with a very modern design for the early 1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The rear parts of the car resembled the future Peugeot 405, while the overall form resembled the Volvo sedans of the mid-1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] A new and more contemporary-looking Anadol logo was developed for the A9.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] The design of the wheels were also characteristic of the European cars of the mid to late 1980s.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] However, the A9 couldn't make it to full mass-production and the prototype was destroyed.
[src:askam-trucks/anadol] Anadol subsequently ceased to exist as a car brand in 1986, as the Otosan factory began producing Ford Motor Company's passenger car models.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] The company, which was also the first truckmaker in Turkey, ceased production in 2011.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] Askam was founded in 1962 as a joint venture with 60% ownership by Chrysler, the company originally traded under the "Chrysler Sanayi A.Ş." name.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] Production of trucks started in 1964 under the Chrysler, Fargo, Desoto, and Dodge brand names.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] Most of the models built utilized a cab and front end developed by Chrysler specifically for manufacture in developing countries.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] This cab, in modified form, continued to be used by Askam until its bankruptcy.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] In 1978, Chrysler sold its share to the local partners and then owners, Tatko, Çiftçiler & Ruşensad.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] Askam continued production under the Chrysler's license agreement.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] Most of Askam's products used Perkins diesel engines.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] After an agreement signed with Japanese Hino Motors in 1991, Askam started production of mini trucks branded "Hino".
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] When Daimler-Benz and Chrysler merged operations in 1998, Askam changed its name to "Askam Kamyon Imalat ve Ticaret AŞ" in 2002 and continued to produce its products under the Fargo and Desoto brands.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] Askam produced a variety of Fargo and Desoto heavy and light trucks of its own designs.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] The numerical portion of the model names (AS250, AS700, AS950) stand for the payload in metric tonnes (e.g.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] In 2003, Çiftçiler Holding became the only owner of the company after acquiring Tatko and Ruşensad shares.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] The last trucks were produced in 2011, and attempts were made to sell or revive the company.
[src:askam-trucks/askam-trucks] While trying to buy Askam from Renault Trucks and Temsa, cooperation with the Chinese truck manufacturer Sinotruk came to the forefront; however, none of the opportunities materialized.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] On 20 January 1971, the organizer of the Frankfurt Motor Show, the Association of the German Automobile Industry (Verband der Deutschen Automobilindustrie – VDA) canceled the show scheduled to be held the following September.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] According to the President of the Association, Dr.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] Johann Heinrich von Brunn, this was because the automobile industry needed to take cost-saving measures to counteract the high costs facing it.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The cost of the exhibition – almost DM 100 million – was considered to be excessive in comparison to the business benefits.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] For the Frankfurt-based fair and exhibition company, Messe Frankfurt, cancellation would have meant a loss of at least DM 1.5 to 2 million in revenues.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] In mid-March 1971, Messe Frankfurt announced that a new event – Automechanika 71 – would be held instead of the Motor Show.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The initiative for this came from the associations of the motor-vehicle and filling station and garage trades that still wanted to present their products.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] Manufacturers of automotive parts account for around 90 percent of exhibitors at the Frankfurt Motor Show.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The first Automechanika was held from 18 to 26 September 1971 and attracted around 400 exhibitors and 75,000 visitors.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The fair was repeated in 1972 and held thereafter every two years in alternation with the Frankfurt Motor Show.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The 25th Automechanika Frankfurt took place from 11 to 15 September 2018.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] 5,000 (2016: 4,820) exhibitors from 76 countries presented their products and services at the fairground of Messe Frankfurt in an area of 315,000 sqm .
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] Around 135,000 visitors from 184 countries came to the show.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] With around 5,000 exhibitors, Automechanika is well established and is one of the most successful trade fair brands in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The latest Automechanika Frankfurt took place from 10 to 14 September 2022.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] Over 2,800 exhibitors from around 70 countries presented their products and services at the fairground of Messe Frankfurt.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] Around 78,000 visitors from 175 countries came to the show.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The 10th Automechanika Buenos Aires took place from 7 to 10 November 2018.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] 451 exhibitors from 17 countries presented their products and services at the fairground of Sociedad Rural Argentina in an area of 35,000 sqm.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] 26,644 visitors from 39 countries came to the show.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] The latest Automechanika Buenos Aires took place from 11 to 14 October 2022.
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] Over 282 exhibitors and 700 brands from 14 countries presented their products and services at the fairground of Sociedad Rural Argentina in an area of 35,000 sqm .
[src:askam-trucks/automechanika] 22,671 visitors from 33 countries came to the show.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The **automotive industry in Turkey** plays an important role in the manufacturing sector of the Turkish economy.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The companies operating in the Turkish automotive sector are mainly located in the Marmara region, especially Bursa.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2023, Turkey produced 1,486,393 motor vehicles, ranking as the 13th largest producer in the world (production peaked at 1,695,731 motor vehicles in 2017, when Turkey also ranked 13th).
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Turkish automotive companies like TEMSA, Otokar and BMC are among the world's largest van, bus and truck manufacturers.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Togg, or Turkey's Automobile Joint Venture Group Inc. is the first all-electric vehicle company of Turkey.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] With a cluster of car-makers and parts suppliers, the Turkish automotive sector has become an integral part of the global network of production bases, exporting more than $35 billion worth of motor vehicles and components.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2017, nearly 85% of exports went to Europe.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Global car manufacturers with production plants include Tofaş, Oyak-Renault, Hyundai Assan Otomotiv, Toyota Motor Manufacturing Turkey, Ford Otosan.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The foundations of the industry were laid in the 1950s when TOE (Türk Otomotiv Endüstrileri A.Ş.) started producing REO military truck and later trucks by International Harvester.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] A brief foray in car production was stopped short.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1961 the first indigenously designed domestic passenger car Devrim was made by train manufacturer TCDD.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] With the establishment of the Otosan assembly factory in 1959, mass production of the domestic car Anadol started in 1966 followed by the mass production of Renault 12 by Renault-Oyak joint venture Mais in 1969.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] On 15 August 1925 the Turkish Aircraft, Automobile and Engine Limited Company (Tayyare Otomobil Türk Anonim Şirketi, TOMTAŞ) factory was founded in Turkey.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1929 the first car was assembled in Istanbul by Ford Motor Company.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] However, production ended due to the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1954 the Jeep factory was established for the production of Turkey's Willys-Overland vehicles in Tuzla, Turkey.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1959 the Otosan factory was established in Istanbul to produce the models of the Ford Motor Company under licence in Turkey.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Production of the Ford Consul at the Otosan factory began in 1960.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1961 four Devrim sedan prototypes were built at the Tülomsaş factory in Eskişehir.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] It was the first indigenously designed and produced Turkish automobile, but it did not enter production.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1964 the production of the Austin and Morris vehicles of the British Motor Corporation began at the BMC factory in İzmir.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The BMC brand was later fully acquired by Turkey's Çukurova Group in 1989, which currently produces all BMC models in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1966 Anadol became the first mass-produced Turkish automobile brand.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] All Anadol models were produced by the Otosan factory in Istanbul.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1968 the Tofaş factory was opened in Bursa for producing Fiat models under licence.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 1969 the Oyak-Renault factory was established in Bursa for producing Renault models.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Other global automotive manufacturers such as Toyota, Honda, Opel, Hyundai, Mercedes-Benz and MAN Truck & Bus produce automobiles, vans, buses and trucks in their Turkish factories.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] There are also a number of Turkish bus and truck brands, such as BMC, Otokar and TEMSA.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] By 2004, Turkey was exporting 518,000 vehicles a year, mostly to the European Union member states.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2006, the European Investment Bank loaned Tofaş €175 million to jointly develop and produce with PSA Peugeot Citroën and Fiat Auto small commercial vehicles for the European market.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The loan, part-financing for total investments estimated at €400 million, was intended to result in an important expansion of the company's production capabilities and create around 5,000 new jobs.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The vehicles will be produced at the manufacturing plant of Tofaş in Bursa with an additional, initial, annual capacity of 135.000 cars, due to roll off the assembly line in late 2007.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The first official introduction of Etox Zafer took place on 30 August 2007.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Like in many countries, the car manufacturing industry was significantly affected by the Great Recession.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In March 2009, Turkey's Automotive Industry Association (OSD) said the automotive production fell by 63% on year in the first two months of 2009, as exports dropped by 61.6% in the same period.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2019, the high automotive export figures were boosted by the substantial increase in sales to the Netherlands and the U.S., which saw a rise of 131% and 55%, respectively.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] According to Uludağ Automotive Industry Exporters.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The opening of the Togg factory in Gemlik is inaugurated on October 29, 2022, the Turkish Republic Day.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The factory was built in a quick time of just over 2 years, with construction having started on July 18, 2020 for a total of 1.2 million square meters.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] During the event, the company was presented by its vision, its mission, its production objectives as well as its approach to users.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] This day also saw the first Togg vehicle, an Anadolu red T10X, come off the assembly line.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In addition, the public was able to learn of the arrival of a 4-door coupé model, the C-XCoupe, in 2026.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2022 Turkey produced 1,352,648 motor vehicles, ranking as the 13th largest producer in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Annual production in Turkey had earlier peaked at 1,695,731 motor vehicles in 2017, when the country also ranked 13th in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2008 Turkey produced 1,147,110 motor vehicles, ranking as the 6th largest producer in Europe (behind the United Kingdom and above Italy) and the 15th largest producer in the world.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The combined capacity of the 6 companies producing passenger cars stood at 726,000 units per year in 2002, reaching 991,621 units per year in 2006.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] In 2002, Fiat/Tofaş had 34% of this capacity, Oyak/Renault 31%, Hyundai/Assan and Toyota 14% each, Honda 4%, and Ford/Otosan 3%.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] With a cluster of car-makers and parts suppliers, the Turkish automotive sector has become an integral part of the global network of production bases, exporting over $22,944,000,000 worth of motor vehicles and components in 2008.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Turkey also manufactures motorcycles as well as electric bicycles, e-scooters and 3 wheelers.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] Turkey aims to produce batteries for these e-vehicles.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] The is a 40% import tariff on Chinese electric cars, whereas the EU and US have 10% and 27.5% tariffs on them.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] As of 2023 health impact assessment is not done in Turkey.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] As of 2025, nearly 18% of new car sales were electric, making Turkey the 4th place in Europe.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry-in-turkey] As of 2025, there were more than 35,000 stations serving countrywide with 2.588 MW installed.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The **automotive industry** comprises a wide range of companies and organisations involved in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing, selling, repairing, and modification of motor vehicles.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] It is one of the world's largest industries by revenue with global automotive market at ~$2.75 trillion in 2025.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The word *automotive* comes from the Greek *autos* (self), and Latin *motivus* (of motion), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] This term, as proposed by Elmer Sperry (1860–1930), first came into use to describe automobiles in 1898.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The automotive industry began in the 1860s with hundreds of manufacturers pioneering the horseless carriage.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Early car manufacturing involved manual assembly by a human worker.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The process evolved from engineers working on a stationary car to a conveyor belt system where the car passed through multiple stations of more specialised engineers.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In the 1960s, robotic equipment was introduced, and most cars are now mainly assembled by automated machinery.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] For many decades, the United States led the world in total automobile production, with the U.S.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Big Three General Motors, Ford Motor Company, and Chrysler being the world's three largest auto manufacturers for a time, and G.M. and Ford remaining the two largest until the mid-2000s.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In 1929, before the Great Depression, the world had 32,028,500 automobiles in use, of which the U.S. automobile enterprises produced more than 90%.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] At that time, the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] After 1945, the U.S. produced around three-quarters of the world's auto production.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by Japan and then became a world leader again in 1994.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production during 2006 and 2007, and in 2008 also China, which in 2009 took the top spot (from Japan) with 13.8 million units, although the U.S. surpassed Japan in 2011, to become the second-largest automobile industry.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced more than 31 million vehicles in a year, after breaking 30 million in 2023, reaching 29 million for the first time in 2017 and 28 million the year before.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced the most passenger cars in the world, with Japan, India, Germany, and South Korea trailing.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] This was achieved by Chinese car companies signing joint ventures with foreign manufacturers.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] From 1970 (140 models) to 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the number of automobile models in the U.S. has grown nearly twofold.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Safety is a state that implies being protected from any risk, danger, damage, or cause of injury.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In the automotive industry, safety means that users, operators, or manufacturers do not face any risk or danger coming from the motor vehicle or its spare parts.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Safety for the automobiles themselves implies that there is no risk of damage.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Safety in the automotive industry is particularly important and therefore highly regulated.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Automobiles and other motor vehicles have to comply with a certain number of regulations, whether local or international, in order to be accepted on the market.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The standard ISO 26262, is considered one of the best practice frameworks for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In case of safety issues, danger, product defect, or faulty procedure during the manufacturing of the motor vehicle, the maker can request to return either a batch or the entire production run.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] This procedure is called product recall.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Product recalls happen in every industry and can be production-related or stem from raw materials.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Product and operation tests and inspections at different stages of the value chain are made to avoid these product recalls by ensuring end-user security and safety and compliance with the automotive industry requirements.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] However, the automotive industry is still particularly concerned about product recalls, which cause considerable financial consequences.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In 2007, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road, consuming over 980 billion litres (980,000,000 m3) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The automobile is a primary mode of transportation for many developed economies.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The Detroit branch of Boston Consulting Group predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand would be in the four BRIC markets (Brazil, Russia, India, and China).
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Meanwhile, in developed countries, the automotive industry has slowed.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] It is also expected that this trend will continue, especially as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanised countries) no longer want to own a car, and prefer other modes of transport.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Other potentially powerful automotive markets are Iran and Indonesia.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Emerging automobile markets already buy more cars than established markets.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 percent of the global light-vehicle sales in 2010.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in BRIC countries.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.8 million units.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In July 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains important guidelines for the future of the automotive industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers including GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover and Mercedes-Benz committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Major car manufacturing nations like the United States, Germany, China, Japan and South Korea, as well as Volkswagen, Toyota, Peugeot, Honda, Nissan and Hyundai, did not pledge.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The global automotive industry is a major consumer of water.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Some estimates surpass 180,000 L (39,000 imp gal) of water per car manufactured, depending on whether tyre production is included.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Production processes that use a significant volume of water include surface treatment, painting, coating, washing, cooling, air-conditioning, and boilers, not counting component manufacturing.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Paintshop operations consume especially large amounts of water because equipment running on water-based products must also be cleaned with water.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] In 2022, Tesla's Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg ran into legal challenges due to droughts and falling groundwater levels in the region.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Brandenburg's Economy Minister Joerg Steinbach said that while water supply was sufficient during the first stage, more would be needed once Tesla expands the site.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The factory would nearly double the water consumption in the Gruenheide area, with 1.4 million cubic meters being contracted from local authorities per year — enough for a city of around 40,000 people.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Steinbach said that the authorities would like to drill for more water there and outsource any additional supply if necessary.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] : US had produced more than 80% of motor vehicles.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] : India overtakes Germany to become 4th largest automobile producer.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The OICA counts over 50 countries that assemble, manufacture, or disseminate automobiles.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Of those, only 15 countries (**boldfaced** in the list below) currently possess the capability to design original production automobiles from the ground up, and 17 countries (listed below) have at least one million produced vehicles a year (as of 2023).
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] All ten remained as the ten largest car makers by sales until the merger between Fiat-Chrysler and the PSA Group in early 2021; only Renault was degraded to 11th place, in 2022, when being surpassed by both BMW (which became the 10th largest in 2021) and Chang'an.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The eighteen largest as of 2013 have remained in the top 20 as of 2017, except Mitsubishi which fell out of top 20 in 2016, while Geely fell out of the top 20 in 2014 and 2015 but re-entered it in 2016.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Mercedes-Benz Group held a combined 6.2% stake in the Renault–Nissan–Mitsubishi Alliance, and the Renault-Nissan-Mitsubishi Alliance also held a combined 6.2% stake in Mercedes-Benz Group until 2021.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] Until 2022, China required foreign automotive firms to form joint ventures in order to access their market.
[src:askam-trucks/automotive-industry] The policy led to quality improvement across the industry.
